<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Committee – Inquiry into the IPCC’s 5th Assessment Report: WWF-UK Response</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; font-size:15pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; padding-bottom:4pt; padding-top:6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by WWF UK (IPC0054)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a science-based conservation organisation working across the world, WWF greatly values the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (IPCC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">periodic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s, the latest of which (AR5) saw its first instalment - the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Physical Science Basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (WG1)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - published on 27 September, 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no other similar science-based international process on any issue of global relevance than that undertak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en by the IPCC, which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both supported and mandated by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the nations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the UN. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main activity of the IPCC is to provide, at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">six-year intervals, assessment r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">detailing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the state of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scientific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">knowledge on climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extremely detailed, peer-reviewed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reports, particularly the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ummary for Policy Makers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (SPM)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vital tool</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in helping to inform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the wider world about the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">body of scientific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that underpins our current understanding of how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anthropogenic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greenhous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emissions are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changing the planet’s climate, how this is likely to impact managed and natural ecosystems and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">human communities, and what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the options </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for adaptation and mitigation responses, both now and in the decades ahead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The latest instalment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> published in September – with its increased expressions of certainty - only serves to reinforce the scientific foundation upon which WWF is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> calling for the urgent decarbo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nisation of the global economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">An Introduction to WWF</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF is the largest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environmental network in the world, with projects in over 100 countries.  One of our key aims is tackling climate change, and, as a result, we have been active in UK and global energy policy discussions for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a decade. We are strongly committed as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an organisation to helping prevent the worst impacts of climate change and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> preventing temperatures from rising above 2ºC compared to pre-industrial levels.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> WWF is an official “observer organisation” to the IPCC.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Based on their scientific ba</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ckground, knowledge and experience, some WWF staff have also been nominated and endorsed by governments as either contributing authors or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reviewers. This process followed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rigorous vetting by the IPCC secretariat, as is the case with all authors and reviewe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs from any institution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including business and industry. However, in the case of the AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WG1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, WWF was not involved as an author or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">officially registered reviewer.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Committee questions</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">report? Have the IPCC adequately addresse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> criticisms of previous reports? How much scope is there to question of the report’s con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">clusions?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R5 WG1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exhaustive, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authoritative lit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> review ever undertaken in the history of science. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hundreds of scientific experts from a wide range of countries and institutions worked on the report either as lead authors or expert reviewers. In the spirit of transparency and inclusiveness, the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report also included a range of climate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “sceptics” as expert reviewers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This, in part, reflected the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IPC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C’s considerable efforts during 2010-2012 to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re-examine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and update </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its formal “principles and procedures”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in light of the InterAcademy Council’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (IAC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2010</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">review into how the IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> function</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> One particularly welcome development adopted by the IPCC following the review was the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improved, uniform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of “quantitative probabilities” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and “qualitative confidence” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in its reports. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In some instances, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he IPCC even went further than the IAC review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example, adopting a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “Protocol for Addressing Possible Errors”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, since its Nobel Prize-winning assessment report in 2007, the IPCC has strengthened its position as the world’s most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authoritative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, rigorous reference source for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the science of climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, therefore, remains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">guide for policymaker</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF sees no reason to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">question the report’s conclusions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In addition, WWF is always open to new scientific evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of views among climate scientists?</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF does not represent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, or claim to represent,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> climate scientists. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is, however, our strong understanding that, based on the list of authors and reviewers, the world’s leading climate scientists and atmospheric </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">physicists were deeply involved and participated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> throughout the whole process. The report had rigorous procedures in place to ensure that a range of views were represented and synthesised in a systematic way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Can any of the areas of the science now be cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">idered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scientists, rightly, resist expressing science in terms of being “settled”. All areas of science can benefit from continued r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esearch. However, the latest repo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rt’s SPM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provides a useful breakdown of each area of climate science</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and where the scientists’ certainty levels currently reside for each. For example, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able SPM.1 on page 5 of the WG1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SPM</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> compares expressions of certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for a range of extreme weather and climate events ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ainst previous IPCC reports.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF is convinced that the level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of “confidence” and “probability” expressed in AR5 that humans are changing the climate system with anthropogenic GHG emissions is m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore than sufficie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt to justify immediate action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by governments and policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">makers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of climate science </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">merit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> further research. For instance, the IPCC is cautious when assessing the negative feedback mechanism to the climate caused by the off-gassing of m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ethane or carbon dioxide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the sea floor or permafrost soils as a result of continued warming under scenari</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">os other than RCP8.5 (the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IPCC’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worst-case scenario). Also, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further advances on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the methodology, data collection and analysis of future climate “extrem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es” would help to improve the IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s expressions of “low confidence” for “Increases of intensity and/or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duration of droughts” and “increases in intense tropical cyclone activity” for the early 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century. Such expressions of “low confidence” were not based on a plethora of contradictory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data, but on the lack of data or representative sophisticated models. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These are just some examples where further research would be beneficial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but none provide a justification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for a lack of action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on reducing GHG emissions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effective is AR5 and the summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for policymakers in conveying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">what is meant by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uncertainty in sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ientific terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPPC has gone to considerable effort – and been very effective - in its latest report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with regard to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> convey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, not just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in scientific terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but also in a way that a non-scientist audience can readily understand. Expressing climate change in terms of risk is also a useful metric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but one that should not be seen as isolated from uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Indeed, being able to better understand and quantify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">degrees of uncertainties only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">serves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to positively inform any risk analysis.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF does not represent, or claim to represent, climate scientists. This is a question best answered by climate scientists t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hemselves.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The latest report does, however, contain a very detailed chapter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(chapter 9</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">examining this precise question.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Additionally, it is shown in the SPM’s condensed figure 6 that “models using only natural forces” fail to explain the observed various</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regional and global land and/or ocean surface temperature increases, as well as ocean heat content growth, compared to “models using both natural and anthropogenic forcings”.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This has helped to identify climate change’s anthropogenic “fingerprint”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Has AR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been a lot of excitable and, in some cases, misinformed media coverage over the past year or so about the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">average </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global surface temperature “hiatus”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Media coverage is not a basis for making policy. However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reacted quickly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incorporate a response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at a late stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> AR5 to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anticipated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> questions from policymakers t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat such media coverage evoked. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WG1 report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provides important context </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in Chapter 10 (p.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 132)</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about the “hiatus” by saying that there are likely to be a range of contributing nat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ural and anthropogenic forcings: “Many factors, in addition to greenhouse gases, including changes in tropo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spheric and stratospheric aerosols, stratospheric water vapour, and solar output, as well as internal modes of variability, contribute to the year to year and decade to decade variability of GMST [global mean surface temperature].”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also showed tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t, despite the “hiatus”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (Figure SP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M 1), the last decade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was the warmest since 1850.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, the cut-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">off for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incorporating papers into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WG1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the deadline was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">31 July 2012 – meant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">latest scientific in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> into this topic was not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considered. For example, the Met Office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, one of the world’s most respected climate science research centres,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> published in July 2013 a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> examining the “potential causes”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It concluded that heat absorption by the world’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oceans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was likely to be an important factor: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Observations of ocean heat content and of sea level rise suggest that the additional heat from the continued rise in atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations has been absorbed in the ocean and has not been manifest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a rise in surface temperature. Changes in the exchange of heat between the upper and deep ocean appear to have caused at least part of the pause in surface warming and observations suggest that the Pacific Ocean may play a key role.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Met Office adde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d in an accompanying report</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the “recent pause…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not materially alter the risks of substantial warming of the Earth by the end of this century. Nor does it invalidate the fundamental physics of global warming, the scientific basis of climate models</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and their estimates of climate sensitivity”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPCC also put short-term natural variations in surface temperatures in the context of long-term anthropogenic GHG atmospheric forcings by stating that up to 40% of “emitted CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will remain in the atmosphere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> longer than 1,000 years.”</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">event dangerous climate change?</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AR5 WG1 report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">asked to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investigate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change. WWF believes, though, that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report made the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scientific case </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for action, particularly with its new “carbon budget” calculations. The report explains in a clear and compelling way that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> species has, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">since the mid-19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> already “spent”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roughly two-thirds of the anthropogenic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carbon dioxide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emissions “budget” that will keep us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - with a 66% probability of success -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2C warming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (widely considered to be the threshold for “safe” w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arming)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On our current emissions “pathway”, we will have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">entire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cumulative budget within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approximately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">two-to-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">three decades. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is WWF’s view that this means the economic case for action is both urgent and compelling. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPCC is due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">publish in spring 2014 the second and third AR5 reports which will deal with, respectively, the impacts of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">/adaptation to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the mitigation options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> WWF anticipat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es that these reports will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further strengthe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the economic case for action.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> WWF joins a range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">major </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">international organisations, ranging from the World Bank</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and IEA</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through to the UNEP</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and OECD</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in arguing the economic case for decarbonisation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What implications do the IPCC’s conclusions in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nationally and internationally?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that AR5 WG1 provides a compelling scientific reason to urgently decarbonise the global economy. It should be used by politicians – both national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (notably, within the UNFCCC process)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – to guide their policy-making. WWF believes that for policymakers to ignore its findings would be both risky and irresponsible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, especially as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AR5 has been accepted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by all participating governments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All policies should be based on, and consistent with, the best available scientific evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge? Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> process is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an inclusive, transparent and rigorous way to collate and summarise thousands of peer-reviewed academic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">papers. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e summaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for policymakers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">then distil this information into a format that can be readily absorbed by a non-scientific audience.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If the process has a weakness it is that the reports have a tendency to be cautious and conservative in their assessment of the evidence. Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s is especially apparent in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the summaries for policymakers, which are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accepted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by all the participant governments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> For example, possible climate change feedbacks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carbon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">release</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> via melting permafrost is not incorporated into the IPCC climate projections due to the large knowledge gaps acknowledged by scientists. However, others organisations, whilst acknowledging the scientific uncertainties about some feedbacks, have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nonetheles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s recognised the need to assess the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> risks. In November 2012, the United Nations Environment Programme published a report entitled “Policy Implications of Warming Permafrost”</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd in November 2013, the UK’s Committee on Climate Change included the “averag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e estimate of perma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">frost, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wetlands and methane feedbacks” into its latest emissions pathways projections up to 2100</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> One proposal being discussed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ahead of the next IPCC assessment report to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improve its up-to-the-minute relevance is that it should ado</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pt a “Wiki” approach</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> so that the latest science can be easily added to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “living” report rather than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continue as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a six-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yearly event</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with a fixed deadline for submissions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent did political intervention influence the final conclusions of the A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">R5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Physical Science Basis summary?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF International is an official “observer organisation”</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is, therefore, entitled to observe how the reports and their summaries are drafted and then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accepted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the participating governments. Such transparency and inclusiveness is a vital part of the IPCC process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Throughout AR5 WG1, WWF observed constructive debate by all gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnments. Points of intervention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> factual, science-based or focusing on improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the clarity of message </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for policy makers. WWF did not observe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a single intervention by any government that questioned the overall substance and/or general messa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge of the report.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the rate at which the UK Government intends to cut CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> emissions appropria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">te in light of the findings of the IPCC AR5 Physical Science Basis report? </span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF-UK firmly supports the Climate Change Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2008</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which places a legal obligation on the UK government to reduce the nation’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greenhouse gas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at least </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">80% by 2050 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">against 1990 levels.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under the Act, the Committee on Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (CCC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was established to provide formal statutory advice to the government on how best to meet this target using a rolling series of five-year “carbon budgets”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The first four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> carbon budge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in law, covering the period from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2008 to 2027, with the overall obligation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have halved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK emissions relative to 1990 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">during the fourth carbon budget period (2023 to 2027)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In November 2013, the CCC published part one</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of its review of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the fou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rth carbon budget, in which it considered the findings of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">latest IPCC report published in September. In light of the IPCC’s latest report, it concluded: “Our climate objective and the global emissions reduction required to achieve it remain feasible, b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ut very challenging. These remain an appropriate basis for policy, both because of the very significant risks associated with dangerous climate change and the costs of delayed-action pathways. An ambitious fourth carbon budget is important to the global pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocess because of the key role of the UK in securing an effective global </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreement.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In part </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">two</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the review, published in December 2013, the CCC concluded that in light of the latest climate change pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ojections presented by the IPCC “i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n order to limit ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sks of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dangerous climate change and preserve close to a 50% chance of keeping temperature rise below 2°C, it is necessary that global emissions peak around 2020, with deep cuts through the 2020s and in the following decades. The currently legislated budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a minimum UK contribution to this global emissions pathway.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in unison with a broad coalition of businesses, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investors and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">civil society representatives</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the carbon budget targets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the Climate Change Act represent the absolute minimum in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">terms of emissions reduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> commitments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the UK in light of the scientific evidence presented in the IPCC’s latest report.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What relevance do the IPCC’s conclusions have in respect of the revi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ew of the fourth Carbon Budget? </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Please refer to the answer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">given </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above (paragraph 11). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">IPCC Principles and Procedures; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.ipcc.ch/organization/organization_procedures.shtml</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Review of the processes and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">procedures of the IPCC, InterAcademy Council, 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/IAC_report/IAC%20Report.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Guidance Note for Lead Authors of the IPCC Fifth Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Report on Consistent Treatment of Uncertainties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, IPCC, 2010; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/supporting-material/uncertainty-guidance-note.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Annex 3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:normal">IPCC Protocol fo